  <h1>How ADA Damages Are Calculated</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Riley Chen (RC), Employment &amp; Civil Rights Practice Lead. Updated May 2026.</em></p>
  <p>ADA Title I damages are governed by 42 U.S.C. &sect; 1981a and mirror the framework available under Title VII. The available remedies include both equitable relief (back pay, front pay, reinstatement) and legal damages (compensatory and punitive). Each category has distinct rules.</p>
  <h2>Back pay</h2>
  <p>Back pay compensates for wages and benefits lost from the date of the unlawful act through the date of judgment or settlement. Courts calculate back pay as: gross wages the plaintiff would have earned minus any interim earnings. The plaintiff has a duty to mitigate &mdash; to make reasonable efforts to find comparable employment. Failure to mitigate reduces back pay by the amount the plaintiff could have earned.</p>
  <p>Benefits (health insurance, retirement contributions, stock options that vested during the period) are included in back pay. Interest on back pay is also recoverable in some circuits.</p>
  <h2>Front pay</h2>
  <p>Front pay replaces reinstatement when returning to the former position is not feasible. Courts award front pay for a reasonable period based on: the employee&rsquo;s age, the availability of comparable positions in the market, and the circumstances of the violation. Front pay is not subject to the statutory cap &mdash; it is equitable relief. Jury verdict data shows front pay awards ranging from a few months to several years of lost income.</p>
  <h2>Compensatory damages</h2>
  <p>Compensatory damages cover: emotional distress and mental anguish, out-of-pocket costs directly caused by the discrimination (job search costs, medical expenses related to the distress), and loss of enjoyment of life. Emotional distress is documented through testimony, medical records, and mental health treatment records. Higher awards correlate with longer duration of distress, documented treatment, and more severe violations.</p>
  <h2>Punitive damages</h2>
  <p>Available when the employer acted with malice or reckless indifference to the plaintiff&rsquo;s federally protected rights. Courts have found malice in cases where: HR was warned of the violation and did nothing, the employer fired an employee within days of an accommodation request, or the employer had prior ADA violations. Punitive damages are not available against government employers.</p>
  <h2>The combined cap</h2>
  <p>Compensatory and punitive damages combined cannot exceed the cap set by employer size: $50K (15&ndash;100 employees), $100K (101&ndash;200), $200K (201&ndash;500), $300K (500+). Back pay, front pay, and attorney fees are <em>outside</em> the cap.</p>
  <h2>Attorney fees</h2>
  <p>The prevailing party in an ADA case may recover reasonable attorney fees and litigation costs under 42 U.S.C. &sect; 12205. In practice, fees often exceed the capped compensatory/punitive damages &mdash; particularly in cases litigated through trial. This is a significant driver of employer settlement incentives.</p>
